ce:section.ce:para:
To test the catalytic properties of the proposed protocol, the miRNA-155 biosensor was utilized with different catalytic properties strategies (Fig. 4
                        ) [15,51]. The change of current responses (ΔI=Ib
                        −Ia, where Ib and Ia are current responses before and after catalysis, respectively) was employed to evaluate the effect of different strategies. Herein, all the assay procedures were performed with the same concentration of miRNA-155 (10pM). As shown in Fig. 4A, it was clear to obverse a ΔI of 18.15μA when the biosensor was incubated with Cu-MOFs only, because Cu-MOFs could catalyze glucose. Besides, when the biosensor was incubated with AuNPs@Cu-MOFs (Fig. 4B), the ΔI was enhanced to 24.95μA, owing to the cooperatively catalytic ability of Cu-MOFs and AuNPs. This phenomenon also indicated the fact that AuNPs@Cu-MOFs hybrid nanomaterial possessed enhanced catalytic ability toward glucose, because the Cu-MOFs nanomaterials with good biocompatibility and large surface area could assembled with AuNPs while enhancing the catalytic signal. The comparison results displayed that excellent nanomaterial (AuNPs@Cu-MOFs) were crucial for final enhancement of detection sensitivity.
